			<tr><td colspan="2">
				<div class="postbody">
				I'd say it's about damn time we perfected some of this promising weapon technology.
<br />

<br />
Generally I think WMDs are bad, because there simply are never that many bad guys. Madmen and despots with an axe to grind against the entire world are the only ones to benefit from that kind of weapon. These other weapon types however are a good thing, especially ones that have high accuracy or low casualty rates, or provide good defense. And it's about damn time we got some working lasers. They are the only thing that can obsolete missile technology.
<br />

<br />
I know they are developing new combat armors using nanofiber technology, spinning the armor from spinneretts just like a spider. It takes a very long time to make even a single piece, but the resulting armor can take a direct hit from a fucking <span style="font-style: italic">tank round</span> and not break. It weights next to nothing too, far less than conventional gear. That's damn impressive. I think I saw this on the "superweapons" discovery series. A soldier wearing this only has to worry about the impact from conventional bullets, because no bullet can actually penentrate the armor. Sounds like something that would be useful in aircraft as well.
<br />

<br />
I've also read about directional bullets... that is, bullets that are smart enough to steer towards a painted target or a heat source. If memory serves, they have grooves on the actual bullet that give it some degree of flight control, and some retractable obstruction in the groove itself to impede or allow airflow. Due to the high speeds, even a tiny change in the groove can result in a decent turn. Wouldn't expect much use out of it in close range, but for spraying a field down or sniping from long range it would be very useful.
<br />

<br />
EMP bombs. They deliver an EMP payload annihilates anything modern in the blast radius. I have read articles about the development of this tech but I've never heard of it being used anywhere. Very handy for sticking your opponent back into the dark ages, and the only casualties are the folks who were using a pacemaker.
<br />

<br />
My favorite one was this fiendish runway killing bomb that was developed by the British. Parts of the bomb were made to look like runway debris, but were actually tiny, motion-sensitive bomblets themselves that became active shortly after impact and detonation of the main payload.. Anyone clearing the mess off of the runway who was unfortunate enough to bump one would get blasted as if he'd been standing on a standard frag grenade. That's such a mean weapon... but it definitely does its job.
<br />

<br />
There will always be someone to fight. Be prepared, or be conquered.<br />
				<span class="gensmall"></span><br />
				</div>
