			<tr><td colspan="2">
				<div class="postbody">
				Laser weapons always end up hitting a brick wall. It is not the power issue. It has to do with the fact that any laser powerful enough to burn through missiles ends up creating plasma in its way: it turns the air it passes through into plasma. Plasma ends up absorbing almost all of the energy. The current (meaning last decade or 2) tricks to avoiding the plasma channel are to pulse the laser. Adaptive mirrors (they bend so that they stay focused even though the beam is wiggling) are another. Making the lasers 100x as powerful won't solve the plasma issue. Using frequencies of light that don't get absorbed by the atmosphere can help. That is why effort is being put into "free electron lasers." The flash you see from lightning is the air turning into plasma. 
<br />

<br />
If you want to build your own CO2 laser, there was an Amateur Scientist column in Scientific American (the particular column was published in 1969) that should have been called <span style="font-style: italic">High School Kids Build Death Ray</span>. A 40 watt CO2 laser will crack bricks, shatter glass and instantly set wood on fire. Please be more careful than I was. Looking back, I am surprised I did not kill or maim myself and my friends. Or burn down northern indiana. Although many folks I know would have been pleased if I did burn it down. Do not use a powerful infrared laser to try to make crop circles. 
<br />

<br />
There was a Scientific American article several years ago (in the 1980s), when SDI was the state religion, explaining how the proposed missile defence systems can't work. And by can't work, they can't work for the same reason that perpetual motion machines can't work: they violated physics. The article also showed 4 simple countermeasures that would totally defeat any directed energy weapon: spinning the missile, using polished metal, pumping small amounts of fluid out the nose cone over the body of the missle or switching to cruise missles. Any system capable of shooting down cruise missiles would also be capable of shooting down passenger aircraft. Can you imagine the headlines? <span style="font-style: italic">Teen hacker shoots down airplanes, film at eleven! </span> It is a pity that the improvements in software development and computer power that would have been needed for SDI still have not shown up. If the necessary improvements in software development had come about, there would be nothing like viruses, computers would be able to talk to you as conversationally as other humans do and programs the size and complexity of Windows would have exactly zero bugs in them while being made on time and on budget.
<br />

<br />
Later in the 1980s there was a staged test where it was claimed that a laser blew up a missle on a stand. It was later shown that this test was publicised to make the Soviets think we had something that did not exist, and it was faked with pyrotechnic charges. Just as fake as NBC'%&$*-em-up blowup." Only this test cost the taxpayers around $180,000,000 to fake. Gotta love how those defense contracters embezzle money with bulldozers and hide it behind "national defense." 
<br />

<br />
Somewhere in storage, is a 1956 Popular Mechanics magazine with a funny thing on the cover that looks like an array of trumpets. It is a sonic weapon that was invented in France that was capable of destroying buildings at a  distance using focused sound waves. It could also emulsify people who were inside tanks (look it up in a dictionary). I do not know why the technology was abandoned, probably had something to do with the ~150dB audio signal tending to emulsify the operators too. Would fit on the back of a jeep and you would need to tow a compressor to power it. Buildings damaged by focused pairs of this weapon looked like they took earthquake damage rather than directed energy. Commercial jet engines are around 110-125dB.
<br />

<br />
Infrasonics can be used to make crowds disperse. Rumors claim that the British have a system which induces nausea, vomiting and uncontrollable diarhea in crowds. Probably just the spice girls tho.<br />
				<span class="gensmall"></span><br />
